# Prose and dashes (enforced automatically)

Two gates back this rule: a `postToolUse` Cursor hook flags dashes the moment
you write them, and a `pre-commit` gate (`prose-dash-gate`) fails any commit
that contains them. Write clean the first time; do not lean on the gates.

## Never emit these characters
- U+2013 EN DASH, U+2014 EM DASH, U+2015 HORIZONTAL BAR: banned everywhere, in
  prose, code, comments, commit messages, and generated card text.
- U+2212 MINUS SIGN: banned in prose. Allowed only in real math or parser code
  (this is an actuarial app), and only when that line carries a `dash-ok`
  comment marker so the gate skips it.

## Use instead
- Range: a hyphen, for example "6-10".
- Aside or interruption: a comma or parentheses.
- A clause break that was doing a colon's job: a colon.

## Cut filler
- Drop these adjectives: comprehensive, robust, seamless, powerful,
  cutting-edge, elegant.
- Drop restatements of the request and after-the-fact summaries.
- Keep a comment only if it explains non-obvious intent, an invariant, or a
  gotcha. Delete comments that narrate what the code plainly does.

## When a file is flagged
Apply the `prose-cleanup` skill (`.cursor/skills/prose-cleanup/SKILL.md`): it
rewrites the sentence instead of deleting the character, then confirms zero
hits. Detection logic lives in `tools/speedrun/prose_dash_gate.py`.
